description:
&lt;p&gt;An exciting opportunity has arisen for a role as a Highly Specialist Physiotherapist working in respiratory medicine at Northwick Park Hospital. This is a fixed term contract for 12 months to cover maternity leave.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Northwick Park Hospital is a major acute general hospital. The Medical Band 7s manage medical HDU (including NIV), the medical wards, an Acute Assessment Unit, and A&amp;E. They also promote early supported discharge in all clinical areas.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Senior respiratory physiotherapists at the Trust are developed to gain extended scope skills of arterial blood gas sampling, chest x-ray requesting and tracheostomy changing and decannulation. There will also be opportunities for on-going clinical and managerial development with senior teaching and support for CPD and internal/external courses.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Summary of the role:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;1. To work jointly with another Band 7 as the clinical lead for the respiratory physiotherapy service for the acute medicine and medical HDU at Northwick Park Hospital.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;2. Be autonomously responsible for assessing and treating own clinical caseload and defining and implementing individualised programmes of care.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;3. To work as a member of the multidisciplinary team (MDT), assessing and treating patients with respiratory problems and/or requiring physical rehabilitation, including complex cases, and maintain accurate and comprehensive patient records.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;4. To work closely with the cross-site Clinical Specialists in leading the development of the Respiratory Physiotherapy Service at Northwick Park Hospital.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;5. To be responsible for the development and appraisal of team members, including Band 5 &amp; 6s, non-qualified staff and Students, to ensure best practice and patient care. This will also include ensuring competency of staff to work on the on-call rota.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;6. To regularly provide formal and informal, on-going training and education to physiotherapy staff, medics, other healthcare professions and students.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;7. To engage in own continued professional development (CPD) and service development, in conjunction with the Clinical Specialist/Consultant as appropriate.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;8. Lead on clinical audit and research within the Respiratory Physiotherapy Service...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;9. .To participate in the weekend working rota (1 in 5 weekends), with time taken back in the following week.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;10. To be the sole physiotherapist on duty in the emergency overnight on-call service.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
